### Next, let us provide the given income statement.

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Alexander Co.}\\
\text{Income Statement}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Sales}&\$42,800.00\\
\text{Cost of Sales}&\underline{35,500.00}\\
\text{Taxable Income}&7,300.00\\
\text{Taxes(23\%)}&\underline{1,679.00}\\
\textbf{Net Income}&\underline{\underline{\$5,621.00}}

\end{array}
$$

### Last, provide the given balance sheet.

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Alexander Co.}\\
\text{Balance Sheet}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lrlr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}&\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Current Assets}&\$17,500.00&\text{Liabilities}&\$37,000.00\\
\text{Fixed Assets}&\underline{68,300.00}&\text{Equity}&\underline{48,800.00}\\
\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$85,800.00}}&\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$85,800.00}}
\end{array}
$$

### Before we can calculate the retention ratio, we need to compute first the declared dividends.

The company maintains a 40% dividend payout ratio. The declared dividends are calculated by multiplying the payout ratio with the net income.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Declared Dividends}&= \text{Payout Ratio} \times \text{Net Income}\\[15pt]
&= 40\%  \times \$5,621.00\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\textbf{\$2,248.40}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the declared dividends are **$2,248.40**.

### Compute the possible maximum increase in sales.

The maximum increase in sales is calculated by multiplying the sustainable growth rate with the current sales.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Maximum Increase in Sales}&= \text{7.42\%} \times 42,800.00\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$3,175.76}}

\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the possible maximum increase in sales is **$3,175.76**.

The following assumptions were made regarding the financial plan:
&nbsp;
* Predicted increase in assets and costs are proportional to sales
&nbsp;
* Dividend payout ratio (40\%) and debt to equity ratio are constant

To determine the sustainable growth rate, let us first compute the return on equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Return on Equity}&=\frac{\text{Net Income}}{\text{Total Equity}}\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$5,621}{\$48,800}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{0.115}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The return on equity is 0.115.**

Now, let us compute the  dividend:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividend}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$5,621}\times{40\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,248.40}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The dividend is \$2,248.40.**

Now, let us compute the retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}-\text{Dividend}\\[12pt]
&={\$5,621}-{\$2,248.40}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$3,372.60}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retained earnings is \$3,372.60.**

Now, let us compute the retention ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$3,372.60}{\$5,621}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.60}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{60\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retention ratio is 60\%.**
